1. Motorcycle Accident Dataset

The mcycle dataset contains measurements of head acceleration recorded during a simulated motorcycle crash (often used in studies of crash helmet performance).

This is a univariate smoothing example: we focus on the relationship between:

  • Time (in milliseconds after impact), and
  • Acceleration (head acceleration at that time)

Our goal is to understand how acceleration changes over time and whether a smooth curve can capture this pattern better than a simple straight line.

In[]:
# ============================================================
# 1) mcycle motorcycle accident dataset (Python / Google Colab)
#   - Equivalent to: library(MASS); data("mcycle")
#   - Uses statsmodels to pull the R dataset directly (MASS::mcycle)
# ============================================================

import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import statsmodels.api as sm

# Load the dataset MASS::mcycle
mcycle = sm.datasets.get_rdataset("mcycle", "MASS").data

# Structure
print(mcycle.info())

mcycle.describe()

2. Simple Linear Regression

As a starting point, we assume the relationship between time and acceleration is linear.
That is, acceleration changes at a constant rate as time increases.

We fit a simple linear regression model:

  • Response (Y): acceleration
  • Predictor (X): time (milliseconds after impact)

After fitting the model, we can overlay the fitted line on the scatterplot to check whether a straight-line assumption is reasonable.

In[]:
# ============================================================
# 2) Simple Linear Regression (Python / Google Colab)
# ============================================================

import numpy as np
import statsmodels.api as sm
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Y and X already defined:
# Y = mcycle["accel"]
# X = mcycle["times"]

# Fit linear model: Y ~ X
X_lm = sm.add_constant(X)          # adds intercept term
lm_mod = sm.OLS(Y, X_lm).fit()

# Summary
print(lm_mod.summary())

Fitted Regression Line

After overlaying the fitted linear regression line on the scatterplot, it becomes clear that the linear assumption is violated.

The acceleration pattern over time shows noticeable curvature and abrupt changes that a straight line cannot capture well. This suggests that a more flexible, non-linear modeling approach may be needed to describe the relationship accurately.

In[]:
# Fitted regression line on scatterplot
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
plt.scatter(X, Y, marker='o', facecolors='none', edgecolors='b', s=20)

# Predicted line
x_grid = np.linspace(X.min(), X.max(), 200)
x_grid_lm = sm.add_constant(x_grid)
y_hat = lm_mod.predict(x_grid_lm)

plt.plot(x_grid, y_hat)
plt.xlabel("Times")
plt.ylabel("Acceleration")
plt.title("Simple Linear Regression Line")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

3. Polynomial Regression

If the relationship between time and acceleration is nonlinear, a simple way to add flexibility is to use polynomial regression.

Even though the curve is nonlinear in X, the model is still linear in the coefficients, so we can estimate it using ordinary least squares (OLS) just like standard linear regression.

A degree-(d) polynomial model looks like:

$$ Y = \beta_0 + \beta_1 X + \beta_2 X^2 + \cdots + \beta_d X^d + \varepsilon $$

3.1 Quadratic

A quadratic regression (degree 2) adds an (X^2) term:

$$ Y = \beta_0 + \beta_1 X + \beta_2 X^2 + \varepsilon $$ In practice, this is done by including (X) and (X^2) as predictors in the model.

In[]:
# ============================================================
# 3.1 Quadratic Regression (Python / Google Colab)
#   R equivalent:
#     quad_mod <- lm(Y ~ X + I(X^2), data=mcycle)
#     summary(quad_mod)
#     plot + lines(fitted)
# ============================================================

import numpy as np
import statsmodels.api as sm
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Y = mcycle["accel"]
# X = mcycle["times"]

# Build design matrix: [1, X, X^2]
X_quad = pd.DataFrame({
    "X": X,
    "X2": X**2
})
X_quad = sm.add_constant(X_quad)   # intercept

quad_mod = sm.OLS(Y, X_quad).fit()

# Summary
print(quad_mod.summary())

In[]:
# Plot scatter + fitted quadratic curve
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
plt.scatter(X, Y, marker='o', facecolors='none', edgecolors='b', s=20)

# For a smooth curve, predict on a grid of X values
x_grid = np.linspace(X.min(), X.max(), 300)
x_grid_quad = pd.DataFrame({"X": x_grid, "X2": x_grid**2})
x_grid_quad = sm.add_constant(x_grid_quad)

y_hat_quad = quad_mod.predict(x_grid_quad)

plt.plot(x_grid, y_hat_quad, linewidth=1)
plt.xlabel("Times")
plt.ylabel("Acceleration")
plt.title("Quadratic")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

The quadratic fit captures the curvature better than the simple linear regression, but that does not automatically mean it is superior.

To formally compare the two models, we can use an ANOVA (nested model) test, since the linear model is a special case of the quadratic model (when the (X^2) coefficient is zero).

  • Null hypothesis ((H_0)): The quadratic term does not improve the fit
    $$ \beta_2 = 0 $$
  • Alternative ((H_a)): The quadratic term improves the fit
    $$ \beta_2 \neq 0 $$
In[]:
# ============================================================
# ANOVA comparison: linear model vs quadratic model
#   R equivalent: anova(lm_mod, quad_mod)
# ============================================================

from statsmodels.stats.anova import anova_lm

anova_results = anova_lm(lm_mod, quad_mod)
anova_results

3.2 Fifth-degree Polynomial

To further increase flexibility, we can fit a higher-order polynomial model, such as a fifth-degree polynomial.

This model includes terms (X, X^2, X^3, X^4,) and (X^5), allowing the fitted curve to adapt more closely to complex patterns in the data. As with lower-degree polynomials, the coefficients are still estimated using ordinary least squares.

However, higher-degree polynomials can overfit the datacapturing noise rather than the underlying trendso their performance should be evaluated carefully using model diagnostics and comparison criteria (e.g., (R^2), adjusted (R^2), AIC, or BIC).

In[]:
# ============================================================
# 3.2 Fifth-degree Polynomial Regression (Python / Google Colab)
# ============================================================

import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import statsmodels.api as sm
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Y = mcycle["accel"]
# X = mcycle["times"]

# Build design matrix with raw polynomial terms up to degree 5
X_poly5 = pd.DataFrame({
    "X1": X,
    "X2": X**2,
    "X3": X**3,
    "X4": X**4,
    "X5": X**5
})
X_poly5 = sm.add_constant(X_poly5)  # add intercept

poly5_mod = sm.OLS(Y, X_poly5).fit()

# Summary
print(poly5_mod.summary())

This model appears to capture the curvature on the left-hand side of the scatterplot more effectively than the previous two models.

However, the improved visual fit comes at the cost of increased model complexity. As the polynomial degree increases, the risk of overfitting also increases, so it is important to balance flexibility with interpretability and generalization performance.

4. Splines

4.1 Regression Splines

In[]:
# ============================================================
# 4.1 Regression Splines (Python / Google Colab)
#   - Fit cubic regression splines using B-spline bases
#   - Compare df = 6 vs df = 10
#   - Plot fitted curves + 95% confidence intervals (mean response)
# ============================================================

import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import statsmodels.api as sm
from patsy import dmatrix

# mcycle is assumed to be a DataFrame with columns: "times" and "accel"
X = mcycle["times"].to_numpy()
Y = mcycle["accel"].to_numpy()

# Sort by X for smooth lines
order = np.argsort(X)
X_sorted = X[order]
Y_sorted = Y[order]

# ------------------------------------------------------------
# Helper: fit spline model and return sorted predictions + CI
# ------------------------------------------------------------
def fit_spline_and_predict(df_value: int):
    X_spline = dmatrix(
        f"bs(times, degree=3, include_intercept=False, df={df_value})",
        data=mcycle,
        return_type="dataframe"
    )
    model = sm.OLS(Y, X_spline).fit()

    # Sort spline design matrix to match X_sorted
    X_spline_sorted = X_spline.iloc[order, :]

    # Mean prediction and CI for mean response
    pred = model.get_prediction(X_spline_sorted).summary_frame(alpha=0.05)

    y_fit = pred["mean"].to_numpy()
    ci_lower = pred["mean_ci_lower"].to_numpy()
    ci_upper = pred["mean_ci_upper"].to_numpy()

    return model, y_fit, ci_lower, ci_upper

# ------------------------------------------------------------
# df = 6 (baseline)
# ------------------------------------------------------------
model_df6, y_fit_df6, ci_lo_df6, ci_hi_df6 = fit_spline_and_predict(df_value=6)

print("=== Regression Spline (df=6) ===")
print(model_df6.summary())

plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
plt.scatter(X_sorted, Y_sorted, marker="o", facecolors="none", edgecolors="b", s=20, label="Data")
plt.plot(X_sorted, y_fit_df6, linewidth=1, label="Fitted Spline (df=6)")
plt.plot(X_sorted, ci_lo_df6, linestyle="--", linewidth=1, label="95% CI (mean)")
plt.plot(X_sorted, ci_hi_df6, linestyle="--", linewidth=1)
plt.xlabel("Times")
plt.ylabel("Acceleration")
plt.title("Regression Spline (df=6)")
plt.legend()
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

4.2 Natural Cubic Splines

Here, the degrees of freedom (df) are specified in advance. We try several values of df to see which one produces a curve that fits the data well without becoming overly wiggly.

In[]:
# ============================================================
# 4.2 Natural Cubic Splines (Python / Google Colab)
#
# Python approach:
#   - Use patsy.dmatrix("cr(times, df=k)") for natural cubic regression splines
#     (cr = cubic regression spline with natural boundary constraints)
#   - Fit statsmodels.OLS
#   - Plot fitted curve + 95% CI for mean response
# ============================================================

import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import statsmodels.api as sm
from patsy import dmatrix

# mcycle is assumed loaded with columns "times" and "accel"
X = mcycle["times"].to_numpy()
Y = mcycle["accel"].to_numpy()

# Sort by X for smooth lines
order = np.argsort(X)
X_sorted = X[order]
Y_sorted = Y[order]

def fit_natural_cubic_spline(df_value: int):
    # Natural cubic spline basis (R's ns(x, df=...) analogue)
    X_ns = dmatrix(
        f"cr(times, df={df_value})",
        data=mcycle,
        return_type="dataframe"
    )
    model = sm.OLS(Y, X_ns).fit()

    # Sort design matrix to match X_sorted
    X_ns_sorted = X_ns.iloc[order, :]

    # Mean prediction + 95% CI for mean response
    pred = model.get_prediction(X_ns_sorted).summary_frame(alpha=0.05)
    y_fit = pred["mean"].to_numpy()
    ci_lower = pred["mean_ci_lower"].to_numpy()
    ci_upper = pred["mean_ci_upper"].to_numpy()

    return model, y_fit, ci_lower, ci_upper

# ------------------------------------------------------------
# Natural Cubic Spline with df = 4
# ------------------------------------------------------------
fit_df4, y_fit4, ci_lo4, ci_hi4 = fit_natural_cubic_spline(df_value=4)

plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
plt.scatter(X_sorted, Y_sorted, marker="o", facecolors="none", edgecolors="b", s=20)
plt.plot(X_sorted, y_fit4, linewidth=1, label="Fitted spline")
plt.plot(X_sorted, ci_lo4, linestyle="--", linewidth=1, label="95% CI (mean)")
plt.plot(X_sorted, ci_hi4, linestyle="--", linewidth=1)
plt.xlabel("Times")
plt.ylabel("Acceleration")
plt.title("Natural Cubic Spline with df = 4")
plt.legend()
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

4.3 Smoothing / Penalized Splines

We can also use penalized (smoothing) splines, which add a penalty term to control how wiggly the fitted curve can be.

This approach has two key advantages:

  • We can use many knots, without carefully choosing their locations.
  • A smoothing parameter automatically balances fit vs. smoothness (helping reduce overfitting).

We will revisit this idea in the next lab when we introduce Generalized Additive Models (GAMs) using the (univariate) Motorcycle dataset.
